_exec_summary.SummaryText:
Sterigenics EO, Inc. previously contracted Radian International (Radian) to assist in addressing the requirements under the federal Risk Management Program as mandated in the Clean Air Act, Sectiion 112(r ) (7).  The Risk Management Program rules requires covered facilities to conduct a hazard assessment, develop a prevention and emergency response program, and submit a Risk Management Plan (RMP) to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) by June 21, 1999.  In 2004, Steigenics completed an update of the original RMP plan by means of using the USEPA software, RMP*Submit.   This update is being submitted via EPA's RMP ESubmit.

Introduction

Facilities that use or store more than 10,000 lbs. of ethylene oxide are required to prepare and submit a Risk Management Plan (RMP) to the US EPA.  The RMP consists of several elements, including an evaluation of potential accident scenarios and a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of regulated chemicals. 

The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that work together to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases to the community.  The RMP includes the following information:
A? Introduction;
A? Facility identification and regulated substances;
A? Policies to protect health, environment, and safety;
A? Hazard Assessment;
A? Prevention Program;
A? Five-Year Accident History;
A? Emergency Response Plan; and
A? Planned Changes to improve safety

Facility Identification and Regulated Substances

Sterigenics operates a contract sterilization facility located Salt Lake City.  The facility is engaged in the sterilization of medical equipment and spices using ethylene oxide.  Ethylene oxide is listed as a regulated toxic substance under U.S. EPA's Risk Management Program regulations (40 CFR 68). 

